*1ï¸âƒ£ Variables â€“ Storing Data*  
JavaScript uses `let`, `const`, and `var` to declare variables.

```javascript
let name = "John";       // can change later
const age = 25;          // constant, can't be changed
var city = "Delhi";      // older syntax, avoid using it
```
â–¶ï¸ *Tip:* Use `let` for variables that may change and `const` for fixed values.

*2ï¸âƒ£ Functions â€“ Reusable Blocks of Code*

```javascript
function greet(user) {
  return "Hello " + user;
}

console.log(greet("Alice")); // Output: Hello Alice
```
â–¶ï¸ *Use functions* to avoid repeating the same code.

*3ï¸âƒ£ Arrays â€“ Lists of Values*

```javascript
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];

console.log(fruits[0]);         // Output: apple
console.log(fruits.length);     // Output: 3
```
â–¶ï¸ Arrays are used to store multiple items in one variable.

*4ï¸âƒ£ Loops â€“ Repeating Code*

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  console.log("Hello");
}
```

```javascript
let colors = ["red", "green", "blue"];
for (let color of colors) {
  console.log(color);
}
```
â–¶ï¸ Loops help you run the same code multiple times.

*5ï¸âƒ£ Conditions â€“ Making Decisions*
```javascript
let score = 85;

if (score >= 90) {
  console.log("Excellent");
} else if (score >= 70) {
  console.log("Good");
} else {
  console.log("Needs Improvement");
}
```
â–¶ï¸ Use `if`, `else if`, and `else` to control flow based on logic.

